classDiagram
    class Owner {
        +str name
        +list~Pet~ pet_list
        +add_pet(pet) None
        +delete_pet(pet) None
    }

    class Pet {
        +str name
        +str animal_type
        +int age
        +list~Task~ tasks
        +add_task(task) None
        +complete_task(task, today) Task
        +delete_task(task) None
    }

    class Task {
        +str description
        +str category
        +int duration
        +str priority
        +str status
        +str recurrence
        +date due_date
        +str preferred_time
        +is_due(today) bool
        +mark_complete() None
        +next_occurrence(today) Task
    }

    class PlanEntry {
        +Pet pet
        +Task task
        +str start_time
        +int start_minutes
    }

    class Scheduler {
        +Owner owner
        +int time_available
        +list~PlanEntry~ plan
        +list~PlanEntry~ skipped
        +filter_tasks(pet, status, category, due_on) list~Task~
        +sort_by_priority(tasks) list~Task~
        +get_single_pet_tasks(pet) list~Task~
        +generate_plan(today) list~PlanEntry~
        +detect_conflicts() list~str~
        +explain_plan() str
        +format_schedule() str
    }

    Owner *-- Pet : owns
    Pet *-- Task : has
    Scheduler --> Owner : schedules for
    PlanEntry --> Pet : refers to
    PlanEntry --> Task : refers to
    Scheduler *-- PlanEntry : produces

    note for Scheduler "One owner, many pets.\ngenerate_plan() pools tasks due today from\nall pets (filter_tasks), sorts by priority,\nfills until time_available runs out. Stores\nplan (included) and skipped (didn't fit).\ndetect_conflicts() reads the placed plan for\noverlaps. explain_plan()/format_schedule()\nread that state instead of recomputing."

    note for Pet "complete_task() marks a task done and,\nfor a daily/weekly task, calls\nTask.next_occurrence() to add a fresh\ninstance due on its next date - this is\nthe recurrence loop."
